419
00:45:59,063 --> 00:46:09,092
Trying to express the fact that there is something in us which does not belong to this phenomenal world, to the world in which we actually live in.

420
00:46:10,994 --> 00:46:17,219
And yet, and this is the paradox, it cannot come to know itself without this world.

421
00:46:18,719 --> 00:46:22,844
And nor can it know what it knows until it tells itself through thought.

422
00:46:24,065 --> 00:46:26,429
And you've all, I'm sure, experienced that.

423
00:46:26,449 --> 00:46:31,775
When suddenly you've said something enormously wise and wondered where it came from.

424
00:46:31,876 --> 00:46:36,320
And somebody said, well, that sounds very wise.

425
00:46:36,340 --> 00:46:47,275
And you say, well... You know, I have this wealth of wisdom which occasionally leaks onto the world.

426
00:46:48,199 --> 00:46:52,806
So, it's really, that's our investigation.

427
00:46:53,286 --> 00:46:59,175
And to, I think it's much easier if you abandon the idea of free will.

428
00:46:59,195 --> 00:47:05,764
And talk much more about what ought I be doing in order to develop my spiritual path.

429
00:47:06,606 --> 00:47:11,974
And then, you know, just abandon the idea, frankly.

430
00:47:11,994 --> 00:47:16,079
So, we've covered quite a bit of ground, really.

431
00:47:17,309 --> 00:47:18,550
I mean, books are written on this, aren't they?

432
00:47:19,090 --> 00:47:21,273
So, you know, dependent origination.

433
00:47:21,994 --> 00:47:28,565
And it's for us to make that a personal, experiential knowledge.

434
00:47:28,585 --> 00:47:30,706
Like, it's something we know through our meditation.

435
00:47:30,827 --> 00:47:31,989
We know the body and mind.

436
00:47:32,009 --> 00:47:33,871
We know the sense bases.

437
00:47:33,992 --> 00:47:36,335
We know the point of contact.

438
00:47:36,556 --> 00:47:40,481
That's when you're down in the knee and you're just feeling sensations.

439
00:47:40,561 --> 00:47:41,983
That's the point of contact.

440
00:47:42,199 --> 00:47:46,025
As soon as the word pain comes up, you're into vedana, right?

441
00:47:46,045 --> 00:47:49,208
You're into the point where you discern things as pleasant or unpleasant.

442
00:47:49,849 --> 00:47:56,518
And then you know this process of desiring, skillful and unskillful desiring, see?

443
00:47:56,938 --> 00:47:58,460
Remember, there is skillful desire.

444
00:47:58,480 --> 00:48:02,826
The desire to sit, to meditate, etc., is a skillful desire, right?

445
00:48:02,846 --> 00:48:05,588
But even so, there's still an I that's doing it.

446
00:48:06,090 --> 00:48:08,492
The fundamental delusion is under there, you see?

447
00:48:09,233 --> 00:48:11,936
But that fundamental delusion is...

448
00:48:12,170 --> 00:48:37,586
through doing what is intentionally wholesome is undermining itself it's undermining that sense of self so one of the great ways of undermining that is through love because through an act of love the sense of I becomes a sense of we so you're undermining it

449
00:48:37,820 --> 00:48:52,989
Even though we talk in a sort of negative sense about the eye, and sort of get rid of the eye and smash it up to pieces and all that sort of stuff, the eye melds into a connection with all beings and with nature and everything.

450
00:48:53,351 --> 00:48:55,896
It sort of becomes...

451
00:48:56,449 --> 00:49:25,478
connected interconnected with it and in that sense it is it's no longer self self-seeking it's no longer selfish because it sees that the happiness of others also is part of its own happiness um that lovely i haven't got it with me unfortunately that lovely prayer of saint francis you know uh may may i may i love rather than be loved see and it's only when we

452
00:49:26,639 --> 00:49:39,190
I mean, one sign, one sign I think of our growing spiritual wealth is the joy of giving something to somebody is greater than the joy of receiving something from somebody.

453
00:49:41,112 --> 00:49:55,126
So when that joy is bigger, it's a little signal to us that actually, you know, the release of the I into a we, into a connection, is part of that undermining of a sense of I.

454
00:49:55,309 --> 00:49:57,152
So what does the Buddha say?

455
00:49:57,193 --> 00:50:05,063
The Buddha says, whatever a teacher can have done for his disciples, I, out of love, out of compassion, have done for you.

456
00:50:06,266 --> 00:50:11,873
And the word he uses is anukampan, which is a sort of word which is moving towards, or giving towards, you see.

457
00:50:14,277 --> 00:50:17,603
So that was, you know, when you look at the Buddha's life, that's what he did.

458
00:50:17,643 --> 00:50:18,804
He became fully liberated.

459
00:50:18,824 --> 00:50:19,865
He didn't just sit there.

460
00:50:20,385 --> 00:50:27,655
glowing in his liberation, you know, with a big sign, and like, leave me alone, you know, not pleasant.

461
00:50:27,675 --> 00:50:31,579
Because, yeah, I mean, he actually gets up, he gets up.

462
00:50:31,960 --> 00:50:47,440
There's a moment of doubt that comes across to whether people would understand what he's got, but he's quick to overcome the doubt when he thinks about his teachers and then his companions, whom he realised were very close to understanding, you know.

463
00:50:49,528 --> 00:50:54,797
And then we talked a little bit about this whole problem of free will and around karma.

464
00:50:55,478 --> 00:51:02,469
And just the suggestion that whether we have free will or not, in a sense, is, I think, slightly off the point.

465
00:51:02,509 --> 00:51:07,335
Because from our point of view, we're coming from a position of not knowing.

466
00:51:07,956 --> 00:51:09,840
And this not knowing is causing us problems.

467
00:51:10,201 --> 00:51:12,364
So our...

468
00:51:12,597 --> 00:51:16,643
aim is correct discernment, to seeing things as they really are.

469
00:51:16,923 --> 00:51:23,695
That's a very common phrase in the scriptures, you know, to see and understand how things have come to be.

470
00:51:24,295 --> 00:51:29,704
It's normally translated as to see and understand things as they are, but it's not.

471
00:51:29,724 --> 00:51:30,646
It's the past pastable.

472
00:51:30,706 --> 00:51:32,530
It's how, in other words, process.

473
00:51:32,590 --> 00:51:34,532
The Buddha's very much into process.

474
00:51:34,974 --> 00:51:37,557
How did we get to where we are, you see?

475
00:51:37,791 --> 00:51:52,306
And then you can see that process and correct it or reinforce it if you see it as beautiful.

476
00:51:52,326 --> 00:51:54,869
And just a final little addition.

477
00:51:55,650 --> 00:52:06,920
When we see clearly what's happening in the present moment, there's no problem with understanding rebirth after death.

478
00:52:08,976 --> 00:52:14,224
It's catching exactly what's happening now that you realise the process is going to be endless.

479
00:52:18,530 --> 00:52:22,637
What confuses us is the identity with this physical form.

480
00:52:22,657 --> 00:52:24,278
That's what confuses us.

481
00:52:24,298 --> 00:52:28,664
So we think that when the physical form drops that's the end of it.

482
00:52:28,684 --> 00:52:34,413
But hopefully at some point you'll discern clearly that the mind is something other than the body.

483
00:52:35,795 --> 00:52:36,215
Essentially.

484
00:52:37,764 --> 00:52:42,652
It's also arising and passing away.

485
00:52:42,672 --> 00:52:45,356
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

486
00:52:45,476 --> 00:52:46,516
Not too confusing.

487
00:52:47,277 --> 00:52:57,693
May you by your sheer moment to moment commitment to mindfulness break through the delusion and arrive at that wonderful place of Nibbana.

488
00:52:57,713 --> 00:53:00,257
Sooner rather than later.

489
00:53:01,097 --> 00:53:03,802
Sadhu.

490
00:53:03,822 --> 00:53:03,942
Sadhu.

